OS/2 EMX import symbol support for GNU binutils 2.30
=====================================================

Enables GNU ld 2.30 to resolve FPC's OS/2 DLL import-by-ordinal symbols
(N_IMP1/N_IMP2 in a.out format). Without these patches, linking any OS/2
program produces "undefined reference to $dll$doscalls$_index_NNN" errors.

ROOT CAUSE: N_IMP1 (0x68) and N_IMP2 (0x6a) symbol types fall within the
N_STAB mask range (0xe0), so stock binutils treats them as debugging
symbols and skips them at multiple points: symbol classification, symbol
table loading, archive member scanning, and — critically — the archive
member *inclusion* test. The last one is the key: even when the symbol
matched an undefined reference, the archive member was never pulled in
because N_IMP1 wasn't in the list of types that trigger inclusion.

THE FIX: seven changes total.

bfd/aoutx.h (6 changes):
  1. Define N_IMP1/N_IMP2 constants and IS_EMX_IMPORT() macro
  2. translate_from_native_sym_flags: classify N_IMP as BSF_GLOBAL absolute
  3. aout_link_add_symbols: don't skip N_IMP at the N_STAB filter
  4. aout_link_add_symbols switch: handle N_IMP in default case (was abort())
  5. aout_link_check_ar_symbols: don't skip N_IMP at the visibility filter
  6. aout_link_check_ar_symbols: ADD N_IMP1 to the member-inclusion trigger
     list (THE KEY FIX — without this the member is never linked in)

bfd/linker.c (1 change):
  7. _bfd_generic_link_add_archive_symbols: strip leading underscore when
     looking up archive index symbols, so stripped references resolve

Apply to fresh binutils-2.30 source:
  tar xf binutils-2.30.tar.xz && cd binutils-2.30
  patch -p1 < binutils-2.30-emx-nimp.patch
  ./configure --target=i386-aout --enable-obsolete --disable-nls --disable-werror
  make

Verified: produces a.out executable with zero undefined references for
FPC OS/2 (i386-emx) programs. Final conversion to OS/2 LX format is done
by emxbind (separate tool, source in ../emxbind/).

